    <div class="text-center">
        <h3 class="display-4">Neapolitan Pizza</h3>
    </div>
    
    <div class="content">
        <p>
            Among my favorite pizzas to eat and make, Neapolitan pizza stands at the top.  While seemingly simple, with the crust requiring only a handful of ingredients, the Neapolitan pizza
            is deceptively complex.  Starting with the crust, we must examine the dough.  While experimenting with different recipes, I have made several discoveries.  The first has to do with
            the flour.  One of the essentials to making a Neapolitan pizza is using a proper pizza oven, something that can reach temperatures of 900 degrees Fahrenheit.  With this comes the need
            for a flour that doesn't overcook at such high temperatures, but also doesn't remain doughy and undercooked in such short cook times.  For me the 00 flour, or "doppio zero" flour, has 
            proven to be the best.  It is a finely ground flour that is perfect for making pizza dough.  
        </p>
        <p>
            While Italian Neapolitan purists will condemn this, I have found that one of my favorite pizza dough recipes is actually a sourdough pizza dough.  The sourdough adds a depth of flavor 
            that is hard to replicate with other doughs.  The sourdough also adds a bit of chewiness to the crust, which I find to be a nice contrast to the crispiness of the crust.  I have also 
            found that the sourdough adds a bit of tang to the crust, which I find to be a nice contrast to the sweetness of the tomatoes and the saltiness of the cheese.  My favorite recipe can be 
            found <a href="https://bakedcollective.com/sourdough-pizza-dough/" target="_blank">here</a>.  I substitute the flour in the recipe with 00 flour, and I use an Ooni pizza oven to cook the 
            pizza to perfection
        </p>
    </div>
    
